Tidyverse: ggplot

Bernard Ade

10-18-2016

ggplot is a powerful data visualization library created by Hadley Wickham. gglot is based on the grammar of graphics which outlines a universal grammar to build plots. This post picks up where the previous post about dplyr ended. I will demonstate the power of combining dplyr and ggplot to create insightful graphs.

rr library(dplyr) library(ggplot2) library(lubridate) library(scales) superstore = read.csv(superstore.csv) superstore = superstore %>% mutate(Order.Date = mdy(Order.Date)) superstore = superstore %>% mutate(Ship.Date = mdy(Ship.Date))

Dataset

rr superstore

Line graph

Basic line graph showing sum of sales by year.

Bar plot

Basic bar graph showing sum of sales by year.

Area Chart

Basic area graph showing sum of sales by year.

Scatter Plot

Basic scatter plot showing relationship between Sales and Profit.

rr superstore %>% ggplot(aes(Sales, Profit)) + geom_point() + scale_y_continuous(labels = dollar) + scale_x_continuous(labels = dollar)

Adding a smooth line to previous scatter plot.

rr superstore %>% ggplot(aes(Sales, Profit)) + geom_point() + scale_y_continuous(labels = dollar) + scale_x_continuous(labels = dollar) + geom_smooth()

Histogram

Histogram showing count of quantity.

rr superstore %>% ggplot(aes(Quantity)) + geom_histogram()

Boxplot

Basic barplot charting discount by category.

rr superstore %>% ggplot(aes(x = Category, y = Discount)) + geom_boxplot() + scale_y_continuous(labels = percent)

Faceting

Faceting divides plots into a matrix of panels. Sales by Region.
